Spring Boot Gradle plugin `1.4.2.RELEASE` does not correctly do `UP-TO-DATE` checks when configured in the `model` block.

I expect that when `bootRepackage` is configured with the `model` that the second execution is `UP-TO-DATE`.

### Example

#### `UP-TO-DATE` when outside `model`

```groovy
plugins {
  id 'org.springframework.boot' version '1.4.2.RELEASE'
}

bootRepackage {
  classifier = 'myclassifier'
  mainClass = 'MainClass`
}
```

Running `./gradlew build` with Gradle 3.3 results in the first build succeeding, second build skips tasks with `UP-TO-DATE`.

#### `UP-TO-DATE` when inside `model`

```groovy
plugins {
  id 'org.springframework.boot' version '1.4.2.RELEASE'
}

model {
  bootRepackage {
    classifier = 'myclassifier'
    mainClass = 'MainClass`
  }
}
```

Running `./gradlew build` with Gradle 3.3 results both `bootRepackage` executing.

I'm using Spring Boot 1.4.3.RELEASE, but the same code exists unchanged on the master branch.

In [`AbstractEmbeddedServletContainerFactory.getExplodedWarFileDocumentRoot()`](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/master/spring-boot/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/context/embedded/AbstractEmbeddedServletContainerFactory.java#L90-L95) is the following check:

```java
		if (file != null && file.exists()
				&& file.getAbsolutePath().contains("/WEB-INF/")) {
			String path = file.getAbsolutePath();
			path = path.substring(0, path.indexOf("/WEB-INF/"));
			return new File(path);
		}
```

If I unzip a Spring Boot "thick war" and run `java org.springframework.boot.loader.WarLauncher` ([as described here](http://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/reference/htmlsingle/#executable-jar-exploded-archives)), it works on Linux (where / is the file separator) but fails on Windows because the path contains "\\WEB-INF\\" instead.

In the current state of Spring Boot `2.0.0.BUILD-SNAPSHOT`, the `@OnWebApplicationCondition` annotation is matched `true` for Spring Web Reactive applications that use Tomcat as an embedded server.

The reason is [this code](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/1df3fb6ecb04048630c1617cb7c465db3407d993/spring-boot/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/SpringApplication.java#L279-L286) in `SpringApplication`:

```java
private boolean deduceWebEnvironment() {
	for (String className : WEB_ENVIRONMENT_CLASSES) {
		if (!ClassUtils.isPresent(className, null)) {
			return false;
		}
	}
	return true;
}
```

Which deduces whether the application is web or not based on the presence of [two classes](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/1df3fb6ecb04048630c1617cb7c465db3407d993/spring-boot/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/SpringApplication.java#L176-L177):

```java
private static final String[] WEB_ENVIRONMENT_CLASSES = { 
		"javax.servlet.Servlet",
		"org.springframework.web.context.ConfigurableWebApplicationContext" };
```

The problem is, the `tomcat-embed-core` jar actually *does* include `javax.servlet.Servlet`. So the `ConditionContext` used for evaluating the condition ends up having as an `environment` an object of type `StandardServletEnvironment`, which is one of the conditions used by `@OnWebApplicationCondition` for determining this is a (Spring Web MVC) web application, as seen in [this piece of code](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/1df3fb6ecb04048630c1617cb7c465db3407d993/spring-boot-autoconfigure/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/autoconfigure/condition/OnWebApplicationCondition.java#L72-L75):

```java
if (context.getEnvironment() instanceof StandardServletEnvironment) {
	return ConditionOutcome
			.match(message.foundExactly("StandardServletEnvironment"));
}
```


I'm not sure if activating `@OnWebApplicationCondition` for Spring Web Reactive applications is actually the desired result –they are web applications after all–, but I doubt it given there are Servlet-bound autoconfigured beans that depend on this condition, like the `ResourceUrlEncodingFilter` being configured in `ThymeleafAutoConfiguration`, as can be seen [here](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/1df3fb6ecb04048630c1617cb7c465db3407d993/spring-boot-autoconfigure/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/autoconfigure/thymeleaf/ThymeleafAutoConfiguration.java#L248-L259). And which currently makes startup fail every time a Spring Web Reactive application with Thymeleaf is run on Tomcat.

